Stukas (1941) Stukas is a 1941 German film, directed by Karl Ritter and starring Carl Raddatz. Karl Ritter was one of the most successful filmmakers of the Third Reich. The film was a huge success, and the 'Stuka Song' sung by the pilots at the end of the film became wildly popular across Germany. Combining actual war footage, special effects, and rousing music, portrays a squadron of Luftwaffe dive-bomber (Stuka) flyers fighting the British and French on the western front in late 1940. The plot largely alternates between combat and story, with the exception of two narratives. In one, three of the flyers who have been shot down behind enemy lines make their way back to the German position, finally succeeding after one of them manages to talk a French unit into capitulating. In the other, a shell-shocked flyer whose doctor has prescribed "A profound experience" recovers the will to fight when he hears "Siegfried's Rhine Journey" during a performance of Wagner's G√∂tterd√§mmerung at the Bayreuth Festival.

Overshadowing the violence and discontent in the early days of the Weimar Republic was a period of incredible inflation. Inflation is a time when the value of money decreases and/or general prices increase sharply. During the war, the German government printed money freely to pay for soldiers, guns, and ammunition. After the fighting ended, there was more money in circulation than there were things to buy. The result was inflation. Prices skyrocketed and the German mark purchased less and less."By the fall of 1923, workers were paid twice a day. After each pay they were given time off to go shopping, so that prices wouldn't rise any further. At the height of hyperinflation, just buying the day's food could cost trillions of German marks; people had to shop with backpacks and wheelbarrows to be able to carry their money -- and many people who had been managing just fine found themselves starving. Behind all the decadence was organized crime, and almost all the major gangs of Berlin had the police on their payroll Many Berliners may well have been having a good time in the 1920s, but there was a darker side to the city during the Weimar period. The German capital was a hotbed of organized crime. Above all, the so-called Ringvereine (or √¢‚Ç¨ÀúRing clubs) ruled the roost. While these criminal gangs had existed since the end of the 19th century, they flourished in the inter-war years, cashing in on the excesses of the Weimar period, especially through their control of drugs, prostitution and illegal pornography. Historians believed that as many as 60 Ringvereine operated in Berlin alone during the 1920s. These were largely made up of First World War veterans, as well as petty criminals and former convicts. However, the gangs also had a significant number of corrupt policemen on their payrolls. This insider help meant that they were often left to go about their illicit business unmolested. Indeed, it was only really when the National socialist came to power and wanted to take control of every aspect of German society that the authorities started clamping down on organized crime in Berlin ‚Äì up until that point, so long as the drugs kept coming, the pornography kept being made available and the backhanders were still being paid, little attention was paid to the city‚Äôs gangsters. According to the local folklore, the Ringvereine honoured a strict criminal code. While they operated protection rackets and fought to control the lucrative drugs trade, they never used violence against √¢‚Ç¨Àúcivilians‚Äô, only against fellow gangsters. To keep the public onside, these criminal gangs also presented themselves as Robin Hood-type outlaws. They always made sure to give a portion of their ill-gotten gains to poor mothers and children. The Sass Brothers were local legends in this regard. Throughout the 1920s, they robbed banks, keeping most of the loot for themselves but also making a point of stuffing stolen banknotes through the letterboxes of homes in working-class neighborhoods. The Saas Brothers‚Äô criminal racket came to a shuddering halt under the National socialists and the pair ended up being killed in a concentration camp in 1940.

Berlin‚Äôs decadent nightlife was hardly a secret at the time. In fact, the city authorities were proud of the fact that their city was one of the most liberal, tolerant and indeed decadent places in the whole world. They embraced the reputation Berlin started to get at the beginning of the 1920s and, as the decade progressed, the scandalous underground scene became increasingly mainstream, with a major tourism industry growing up around it. Alongside the official Berlin tourist board advertisements, a large number of guidebooks offering visitors an insight into the racier parts of the city were published during the Weimar period. One of the most popular was Curt Moreck‚Äôs Guide Through Depraved Berlin. As the title suggests, this guidebook shunned the usual palaces and parks and instead pointed the curious visitor in the direction of homosexual bars like the Topp, transvestite cabarets and places they could pick up a girl (or boy) for the night. Similarly, Ruth Margarete Rolling wrote a popular guidebook to lesbian Berlin, advising readers that there was something for everyone in the city: ‚ÄúHere, each can find their own happiness, for they make a point of satisfying every taste,‚Äù she said. Even traditional guidebooks couldn‚Äôt help mentioning the seedier side of the city. And while some warned visitors to stay away from the many √¢‚Ç¨Àúdens of sin‚Äô, this would often have quite the opposite effect. By the mid-1920s, many were already complaining that the Berlin scene was over. Curious tourists were filling the tables of the main cabaret clubs, much to the annoyance of local artists and writers. Soaring demand meant that the illegal pornography industry boomed during the Weimar years ‚Äì with celebrity lookalikes especially popular Along with drug use and prostitution, pornography also enjoyed a golden age during the years of the Weimar Republic. Making full use of the latest photographic technology, both amateur and professional porn producers struggled to keep up with the insatiable demand of the Berlin public. Much of this was produced by seemingly respectable photographers. By day, they would take family portraits, but by night they would switch their focus to making adult images. Similarly, the booming movie industry of the 1920s was also complicit. Directors and cameramen would often have a nice sideline making some of the first porn films after-hours in the big studios. Of course, the quality of such pornography varied considerably. Some of it was obviously amateur, but some of it was slick and professionally done, with an eye on the aesthetics not just the erotic. The cheapest images could be purchased under-the-counter at most street new kiosks (strictly speaking, indecent images were still illegal) though for the more discerning viewer, more expensive images could be purchased, if you knew where to look, of course. Above all, pornography featuring models who bore a striking resemblance to the biggest movie stars of the day, such as Marlene Dietrich or Greta Garbo, were in high demand. Such models could charge a premium for their services and producers would charge a small fortune peddling the finished product out of cabaret clubs. However, pornography wasn‚Äôt just about sex. In many cases, it was used as a satirical tool, too. There was a healthy market for nude or suggestive pictures of models who looked like Kaiser Wilhelm II or certain leading politicians. While the authorities would often turn a blind eye to most porn, even images featuring underage models, pressure from their bosses meant that the police would often come down hard on producers who dared to associate the former monarch or the country‚Äôs political elite with such adult material.

The public loved to read all about a good homicide case, especially if the victim was young and pretty Berlin in the 1920s wasn‚Äôt just a city of decadence ‚Äì it was a city of violence, too. With crime gangs battling for control of the booming trade in drugs and prostitutes, murder was all too common. But gangster killings weren‚Äôt the type that really excited the Berlin public. Instead, the people of Weimar Germany developed a fascination for so-called lustmord, that is lust-fueled murders, ideally of pretty young women by spurned lovers. If there had been a murder, especially a lustmord, then newspaper sales were guaranteed to soar. Not only would a report of such a crime include all the grisly details, it would also feature gruesome crime scene photographs and any other potentially titillating information, especially if it related to the sexual life of the victim. Far from fair and neutral, the press coverage of murders of young women was sensationalist and often downright misogynistic. So, when it emerged that a serial killer was at large in the west German city of Dusseldorf, the public were gripped. The so-called Dusseldorf Monster (also known as the Vampire of Dusseldorf), committed a string of sexual assaults and murders in the city between February and November of 1929. People couldn‚Äôt get enough of the case. Newspapers devoted entire sections to the crimes, focusing on the sexual aspect of the attacks. Fictional accounts of the murders appeared on book-stands and these too sold like crazy. And then, when Peter Kurten was arrested, convicted and executed for the Dusseldorf murders in 1930, a movie version of the whole affair was in the cinemas within a matter of weeks. Needless to say, it was a box office smash. Such a fascination with lust-fueled murder was also evident in the literature and art of Weimar Germany. Pulp fiction was big business, with most books featuring young, sexualized female victims. Similarly, the paintings of Otto Dix and George Grosz, two of the biggest artists of the Weimar era, often featured mutilated female bodies. Some modern scholars now see the art of the era as profoundly misogynistic, getting a kick out of sexual murders almost celebrating violence against women.

On today‚Äôs broadcast of Call Sign: Werewolf, I break down the questions that no one can answer for you or sell you, so that you can answer for yourself: Who You Are What You Are Why You Are Life‚Äôs not waiting, and you won‚Äôt ‚Äúdiscover yourself‚Äù like a hidden waterfall on a tropical island. Being certain and confident requires answers to these things - not tomorrow or someday, but now. LISTEN HERE

One of my daily mantras: ‚ÄúI know who I am. I know what I am. I know why I am.‚Äù Encapsulated in this simple prayer is the acknowledgement of my ancestors, and recognition of my duty to them and the strengthening of myself and my family line as an act of worship. The understanding that we do not choose *who* we are nor ‚Äúdiscover‚Äù it. We are who we are from birth and blood - *what* we are, on the other hand, is determined by our actions. Finally, that ‚Äúwho‚Äù and ‚Äúwhat‚Äù require a ‚Äúwhy.‚Äù A life lived for purpose, in service of an ideal higher than our own self. Committed to becoming the highest expression of our genes, and the current spearpoint of our entire ancestry, rushing behind us like a waterfall of blood.

A thought: If we constantly look at everything as a ‚Äúproblem‚Äù to which we must find a ‚Äúsolution‚Äù we find ourselves endlessly put upon - Somehow aggressed by the universe. If we instead agree that we were born as men into a life defined by struggle; then these are not problems. Merely choices we make. Minor course corrections and slight navigational movements. It does not become us as men to view all of these minor obstructions as ‚Äúproblems.‚Äù I don‚Äôt look at tying my shoes as a problem. I don‚Äôt stress about waking up in the morning. To be anxious or ‚Äúproblem oriented‚Äù is effeminate and unproductive. Be certain. Navigate the terrain. Believe in yourself. Have faith in your capabilities to overcome and to conquer. Don‚Äôt lose heart and become someone who defines themselves by their ‚Äúproblems.‚Äù Be known as a walking solution.

AND YET To truly live is to have a will, an identity, a thumos that demands more than the slavery the world offers. Slavery in the ancient world wasn‚Äôt considered a sin by the enslavers ‚Äì it was held against the slaves themselves, who lacked the dignity to risk or take their own lives rather than be the tool of someone else. Today, we are faced with the same choice. We must fight to prove we are free. It‚Äôs tempting to just stay in cover and never emerge, to take what they‚Äôve given us. Yet the truth is they have left nothing for us. It seems hopeless. So why then is there this flame in the darkness? Why is there a flag, torn and covered with blood, being raised above the mud? People are terrified. They have little and are scared of losing more. And yet, people keep finding their way to the banner of strength. They cut off our communications. They steal our money. They promise to expel us from society. And yet, operatives still gather ‚Äì at this moment ‚Äì around fires throughout the world. They use their lackeys to publish lies and libels against us. They use their greatest strength, their utter domination of media, to try to define who we are and what we are. And yet, people throw it off, looking past what they have been told, claiming their own identity and making their own judgement. Their most dedicated slaves directly threaten us with harm or death. They send their insults, boasting that they will spill our blood and sack our holy places. And yet, when the moment comes, they are nowhere to be found, and the only fires that rise are our own. The endless war saps the time, energy, and spirit of the strongest souls. Families don‚Äôt understand. Friends don‚Äôt want to get involved. Women grow jealous of something that takes away attention. And yet, at every event, at every retreat, at every ritual, men travel hundreds of miles or cross oceans to be with people they have never met to experience something they don‚Äôt yet understand, and walk away forever changed. The world tells us that it is perverse to seek strength, competition, and struggle. It tells these ideas are outdated, and we need to ‚Äúreimagine‚Äù masculinity itself for our own benefit. And yet, it‚Äôs only after conflict and competition, when men spill blood fighting against each other and then embrace afterward, that we get some small glimpse of what friendship could be. The screens offer us virtual adventures, virtual sex, virtual missions, virtual meaning. The dopamine hit makes it difficult to tear away from the tempting, passive consumption. And yet, people do rip themselves away, and instead seek real adventure, real danger, and real brotherhood in tests of body, soul, and spirit. Faith once had the power to shatter kingdoms and move men to surpass their fear of death itself. The sense of ecstasy, of something beyond mere life, of something that is truly separated from the mundane has been altogether lost. Worse, those trusted to safeguard such traditions seem uninterested in them, instead eager to search for relevance from those who despise them. And yet, men seek the new temples in the forests, those eternal things that lie behind the veil of blood and fire. The oaths spoken at ritual have a greater meaning than any written words. Most of all, the world tells us that you must not leave the path that is set out for you. If you associate with this person, read these things, watch this video, use this symbol, go to this place, attend this meeting, wear this clothing ‚Äì you are finished. The supposed promises of the ‚ÄúOpen Society‚Äù disappear overnight with the most powerful people in the world desperately seeking to control what people can say, read, see, and think. The law offers no protection. The costs of disobedience are real and terrifying. Some of the men who speak the boldest are the quickest to fold when the struggle ceases to be a game. And yet, countless people overcome it all, turn their back on those demanding they debase themselves, and put loyalty above all‚Ä¶‚Äù

cleaned_message: The Valiance Campaign was an initiative I ran for a full month in 2023 for a group of 180 people. It was a full 30 days during which time I worked on no other projects and gave my full attention to making this the most comprehensive and complete expression possible of a simple idea: Providing the individuals who undertook the Campaign with me an organized framework of self-reflection, followed by a concrete decision making process and clear action plan regarding what I see as the biggest challenge for individuals in this Kali Yuga. Deciding on (not ‚Äúdiscovering‚Äù) their personal meaning, purpose, compass and structure around which to live their lives, followed by the physical, mental, and spiritual technologies and tools necessary to then discharge that duty over the long term. The entirety of this initiative has now been edited, reassembled, and presented here for those who were unable to take part in the 2023 group. Included in the Valiance Campaign materials are a workbook for the course that includes clear instruction on how to use the content provided, in what order, an extensive reading list, as well as all the written material that goes along with the centerpiece of the project - Over 3 hours of the most personal, insightful and useful video I could put together, coupled with complementary and extensive audio files, to provide an entire month (and well beyond) of material. All video and nearly all of the audio is exclusive to this course and not found anywhere else - some of the audio had been released before, but only to specific lists or alongside other private paid projects. Outside of my personal coaching packages that I offer at certain times of the year, which range from a single call at $150 to a month of coaching for $1000, this is the closest thing available to a direct, intensive coaching and mentorship program I‚Äôve ever released - all for $50. GET ACCESS HERE Here, you can see what many of the people who did the original Campaign (which they paid between $100 to $500 for), had to say about it: ‚ÄúThis campaign has been really good for me. Reevaluating my goals, personal code, and strategies has been of a great help and has been very motivating personally. I thank you for all the work you put in and appreciate the progress you have helped me make in my life, through your work.‚Äù - David C. ‚ÄúGreat campaign. I came into it limping, having just barely emerged from yet another rough patch‚Äîself inflicted, as usual. I'm in a much stronger state now than I was a month ago, thanks largely to the structured assignments‚Ä¶ It was definitely too much to cram into one month, and I think this was the point. This is material that is worth revisiting, deepening, and refining repeatedly.‚Äù - Y. ‚ÄúThe best thing that I can say about Valiance Campaign, the only thing that ultimately matters is that now I feel firmly on track, walking a Way that is my own, that reflects what I am and what I want to become. There have been lapses, moment in which I struggled to make time , moment in which I had to run to keep pace; there are things on which I'm still working, reflecting; actually on most of the things of this Campaign I'll never cease to strive, to work, to polish, to temper for the rest of my life.‚Äù - Matteo ‚ÄúLet me also express my gratitude for this campaign. Training is much simpler than today‚Äôs internet coaches make it. It‚Äôs their job to make it sound more difficult and complex. Work with someone knowledgeable about correct form when you begin training. From there: train heavy, train hard, and train often while maintaining a diet that isn‚Äôt trash. You‚Äôll be fine. Immerse yourself in the basics and solid fundamentals, and you‚Äôll get strong and look the part, too. Hope you all hit it hard today. (Also to put it nicely, many of these folks don‚Äôt have the credentials in physique or numbers to really make them anything close to an authority. Franco Columbu said no one would ever need weighted pull-ups if they would actually learn to do an unweighted one correctly. This simple statement has so many carryovers to everything else we do. No one with good judgement cares about someone‚Äôs capacity at anything if it‚Äôs slop, uncontrolled, ugly, careless. The way we perform our reps in the gym, on the mats, in our lives - this says a great deal about us. No half-reps. No loss of control. No half-hearts. (Today‚Äôs bench session: 135x10, 225x10, 315x3, 335x1, 315x2, 275x5, 225x12 with every rep under slow control)

Various training modalities over the years, always with a few things in common: ‚Ä¢Intense focus on each rep ‚Ä¢All reps always performed at challenging weight for that set‚Äôs target rep goal ‚Ä¢Variation between heavy/intensity days and volume/higher rep days within the same program ‚Ä¢Adequate recovery time ‚Ä¢Eating centered around desired physical goal ‚Ä¢Ball-busting effort on every workout ‚Ä¢No wasted time between sets - adequate rest, then back at it, resulting in ‚Äúshort‚Äù workouts of 35-60 mins. https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/i18zq6lz1z4t9no5t7tk9/4-FEROCITY.mp4?rlkey=f4wqd8kcdl6v9oc9cryzudoju&dl=0

From the cross and the swastika to the corporate logo or the humble arrow, symbols have been used throughout history to convey information, to focus intention and create identity, and have been weaponized as mind control and propaganda. ‚ÄúDid you have a good world when you died?‚Äù The above is a quote from Jim Morrison‚Äôs ‚ÄúAmerican Prayer.‚Äù I‚Äôve always liked his use here of the term ‚Äúworld,‚Äù not ‚Äúlife.‚Äù It‚Äôs a cowardly idea, unsuited to men of action, to not do whatever is in our power to leave this world a better place for our passing, and not just our passing, but our direct work upon it. Men are so riddled these days with despondent ideas and the foul reek of despair. They say ‚Äúthe world is shit,‚Äù or ‚Äúeverything is fucked.‚Äù True enough. But they say these phrases with an air of finality. An air of powerlessness - the suggestion in their voices and their punctuation that there is nothing to be done about it. I want my death to be an exclamation mark, not a period. I want my life to not be a statement of the finality of evil and darkness, but a continuation of those phrases. ‚ÄúThis world is fucked - therefore, it falls to me and to my brothers to war against the forces that despoil it, and to show that it can be improved, repaired, resacralized, made new.‚Äù Today‚Äôs broadcast of Call Sign: Werewolf explores the topic of the high magic of ideation, creation, synthesis, and the mythic life. ‚ÄúManas is one of the four parts of the mind in Hindu thought, representing the faculty that with the help of the sensory organs, receives information from the world around us and presents it to the intellect. It is the instinctive mind, as well as the individualizing principle that allows man to see himself as an individual, separate from the collective. It is the seat of desire, as well, that undisciplined aspect of self that creates and moves us toward actions for the sake of satiating ourselves in some way or another. It is divided into two parts, the ‚Äúbuddhi manas‚Äù and the ‚Äúkama manas‚Äù which refer to the ‚Äúhigher mind‚Äù and the ‚Äúlower mind,‚Äù another idea that has resonated strongly with me and been discussed often in my writing. Even in the shape of the *Mannaz rune, we can see two separate vertical lines ‚Äúcommunicating‚Äù with one another with a kind of ‚Äúwiring‚Äù that goes from one to the other and crosses in the center, creating a pictogram of balance, interconnectedness, and exchange. The rune itself also indicates the idea of man in his highest potential- what he is ultimately capable of if he is performing at the greatest level possible through training the lower mind to be ruled by the higher mind. One of the techniques through which this can be encouraged is that of mantra. The word itself connects to the subject at hand, and is a Sanskrit word made up of the root, manas, and the suffix -tra, denoting a tool or instrument. Taken together, a ‚Äúmind tool,‚Äù or ‚Äúinstrument of consciousness.‚Äù‚Äù https://operationwerewolf.com/war-journal/2018/03/02/mannaz-and-mantra/

Read so many books ‚Äúyour‚Äù ideas become whatever you read last, but never go beyond the idea stage. Set aspirational goals you‚Äôll never attain because you‚Äôre in love with ‚Äúgoals‚Äù and not action. Criticize everything for not being ‚Äúoptimal,‚Äù or not in line with your meme-washed version of the way the world should be. Build nothing, because you‚Äôre too busy arguing over the best political ideology for a state/country that doesn‚Äôt exist. Spit stoicism for cool points, but act emotionally and irrationally because knowing quotes doesn‚Äôt equate to self improvement. Spend as much time as possible on the internet and in the city while extolling the virtues of nature. *has less than 500 bucks in the bank and also can‚Äôt pull that number off the ground:* ‚ÄúDM me for personal coaching or fitness instruction.‚Äù Wait a moment. Take a breath. Let‚Äôs start over. Why don‚Äôt we try reading for inspiration and to elicit right action, without becoming nothing more than armchair philosophers; Set our sights, pull the trigger and achieve daily, creating a lifestyle of positive habit rather than far-off goals we do not live in a fashion to accomplish. Let our criticism be constructive, and let it begin with ourselves; Enthusiastically build the world we want, instead of empty talk about taking it over. Learn self-control rather than trying to control others. Walk our talk and be who we are - if our lives are in line with our values, people will see who we are and we won‚Äôt need to tell them. Order our own lives before presuming to help others with theirs. Growth and victory come about from engaging in right action. If you‚Äôre not doing much but talking, don‚Äôt slow people down by criticizing them while they are.

cleaned_message: Some days, it feels like life has it out for you. Like every admonishment to ‚Äúkeep your chin up‚Äù is an invitation to get strangled. But it doesn‚Äôt - not really. This kind of mindset is one of victimization and, at the same time, narcissism - the universe itself ‚Äúhas it out for you?‚Äù Take a deep breath. Maybe put your chin down today, and just stay focused on the work rather than worrying about the result. Put one foot in front of the other. And then, after a while, once things settle down‚Ä¶put your chin back up. Everything is transitory - the good and the bad. Whatever you‚Äôre going through won‚Äôt last forever‚Ä¶ You‚Äôve got this, like you‚Äôve weathered everything else in the past. I‚Äôm pulling for ya.

The first new print offering from Operation Werewolf will be ‚ÄúA Kali Yuga Survival Guide.‚Äù Done in the unmistakable raw style and aesthetic of the ‚Äòzines that started the whole thing, AKYSG will collect a series of essays together, including unreleased Transmissions from the early days of Werewolf, as well as brand new, unseen pieces. Throughout the printed work, codes will be included that will take the reader to an interlinked set of videos and audio files recorded for this project by Paul W. These, combined with the writing, will act together as powerful reminders, relentlessly positive hyper-sigils of hope, overcoming, ferocious belief, and tough love- tools to survive a world that seeks to entrench us in apathy, nihilism and despair. Coming soon.

It is not helpful or correct to endlessly fixate on ‚Äúwhat‚Äôs wrong.‚Äù We already know that the pervasive spirit of this era is filthy, dripping with venom, enervating to the soul. Everyone with eyes and truth in their heart can see this. Rather than acting as twigs in the river, thinking we can simply stand against the strong current- let us carve channels instead that direct a portion of the flow into wholesome places. The presence of wolves in an ecosystem reforms the entire environment and changes even the physical landscape as well. This is done simply by wolves continuously acting in accordance with their nature. XCII

For those interested in learning more about Operation Werewolf, here is a suggestion: Start by reading ‚ÄúWerewolf Manifesto,‚Äù available on Amazon etc. If that slim manual resonates, proceed to familiarizing yourself with the free materials of the War Journal on our site - articles go back over 6 years. You can read older essays in the books ‚ÄúComplete Transmissions‚Äù of which there are currently 3 volumes. Inner Circle is another collection of essays, newer than the others. Complete Zines gives a look back to the very beginning of Operation Werewolf, as well as holding some of the esoteric writing from the older days, like Stadhagaldr and ‚ÄúOn Magic.‚Äù Vakandibok is an esoteric work entirely, and as such, may appeal to a slimmer audience. I‚Äôve written other books as well, but the aforementioned are the current Operation Werewolf ‚Äúcodex,‚Äù until a newer one comes out. I hope this helps some of you find your way.

Summer Solstice is the longest day of the year, and the shortest night. This means that from here on, the nights are growing longer, and our time in the light is shorter. The carefree Dionysian spirit of spring must give way to the Apollonian discipline and order of the next cycle. We have work to do. Website restored, original War Journal remains intact, new transmission being typed now. www.operationwerewolf.com

Perfection is impossible to attain, unless, perhaps, one turns their life into a single line of poetry, written with a splash of blood. I‚Äôm still bleeding. Still trying. Still living. And in the recent months, still realizing that politeness and compassion are always going to be good things, but my weaker self doesn‚Äôt need as much compassion from me as I sometimes allow myself to believe. It needs an Iron Fist. And when I feel myself tapping on my own shoulder, saying, ‚Äúcome on. This way,‚Äù and I ignore it‚Ä¶ I need a hammer to the face. That‚Äôs what Operation Werewolf always was to me, and some people got that and resonated. It was an exaggerated version of something, a concept deliberately over the top from its inception in that little notebook, terminologies, aesthetic and all, designed to shatter excuses with a sledgehammer and shake things up, to get The Fire burning. I guess I, for one, still need that. My higher self is still calling from somewhere in space and time, willing my current self to be like him. Maybe that‚Äôs what enlightenment is, after all: Listening to some version of yourself that exists somewhere, someplace, that is the best version of you that will ever be, in any reality, and doing everything you can to line up with that in this one we‚Äôre living in now. I‚Äôm sitting in a tiny cabin in the woods typing this out to myself. But I‚Äôm typing it to you too. Whoever you are, reading this. Maybe you feel like the world is a dark place, and you are alien to it, and uncertain of where to go, or what to do. I‚Äôve felt like that. Maybe you feel, as Hemingway said, that this world is a fine place, and worth fighting for. I feel that, too. Fuck their world, but let‚Äôs not throw the good out with the bad. We should be neither misfits nor miscreants, outcasts or ‚Äúoutlaws,‚Äù save from the world they‚Äôve built without our consent. Instead, we must, as ever, build our own while braving theirs. This can be done, and we will see miracles and radical changes in our own lifetimes. I believe this with every ounce of my burning heart. But in order to do it, we will need three things: Strong limbs. Pure hearts. Actions matching words. Welcome back, or, welcome aboard. Standby for further transmissions. XCII - Paul Waggener, Summer 2022

There was always going to be a return to this thing. In some form or another, for me, it was inevitable. For as many bad things as it created or were done in its name, it was always the source of expression I resonated with the most of anything I‚Äôd ever worked on. This was because I did my best to communicate with myself. I was unconcerned with ‚Äúmaximal reach.‚Äù There were specific things done, and set into place to ensure, from the beginning, that it wouldn‚Äôt be something that was able to have a broad reach. I was looking to reach myself. That is, I was looking to touch that part of myself that was the self I always had wanted to be, to aspire to, and ultimately, upon attaining, realize that I had only reached another false summit. On my best days, I felt like my writing didn‚Äôt even come from the ‚Äúme‚Äù that was sitting at the table pounding away on the keys - rather, it seemed to me when I really ‚Äúnailed‚Äù it, that it was some future version of myself speaking back through time‚Ä¶ Extending a hand to the ‚Äúme‚Äù that existed now, saying ‚ÄúThis way. I can help you get there.‚Äù Ultimately, what created a necessary long ‚Äúcessation‚Äù of above ground, publicly accessible transmissions, was what I saw being done ‚Äúunder the banner‚Äù of OPWW, so to speak. Morons, cop-magnets, real cops, and ultimately people not interested in evolving and moving forward as human beings but remaining mired only in the ‚Äútrappings‚Äù of the project, that is to say, only the exterior ‚Äúhard signal‚Äù aesthetic. I won‚Äôt judge them too harshly - after all, it was my creation. But I would watch, from some cave on the coastal rocks of the Northwest, from an ancient cobbled street in old Europe, from the back of a bar in Appalachia, from the edge of the fire in the dark woods, and I would see: None of them. The real quality of the Operation was what it brought out during difficult to attend and difficult to participate in events, and moreso, lifestyle. I found friendships and brotherhood that exist to this day from those years, with individuals from quite literally, around the globe. Men of action, men of honor, men of worth. Trappings don‚Äôt mean shit. A porno mag can be stuck inside a copy of the Gutenberg Bible, and it‚Äôs still just vile smut. Tee shirts, tattoos, slogans, all the rest- it didn‚Äôt matter whether I had created them or not‚Ä¶it was how I saw them used over and over again that disheartened me and made me step back in order to find a solution. The solution was: See who was still there when the dust settled, and who was miraculously long gone. Whose lives looked the same after they discovered Werewolf, and after Werewolf was ‚Äúover?‚Äù Who understood well enough the appellation itself, and all that implied, so eloquently put into song by friends of ‚Äúour thing,‚Äù black metal titans Marduk: ‚ÄúWerewolf riding the end times Werewolf behind enemy lines‚Ä¶‚Äù So, I did just that. I watched and I kept contact with those who kept contact with me. Those still ‚Äúliving it.‚Äù It was few enough compared to the hundreds or thousands who had claimed some kind of ‚Äúassociation,‚Äù but it was men I had bled and sweated with across the face of the earth, and I had no interest in abandoning those connections, and never did. We kept talking. Our crews stayed training, working together to build a good life among the ruins of the modern world. I used the time to broaden my experience, and my horizons. I increased my skill, widened my network, elevated my leverage. All the time, I was doing the things that I said I would do when I began Operation Werewolf in that little beat up black notebook that I still keep like a holy relic: ‚ÄúOperation Werewolf is rabid fucking resistance,‚Äù it began, as it delivered to me an edict from my higher self of how my life would be lived. I did not attain perfection adhering to that edict. I let myself down many times. But the Operation, as many of us have often said, is ongoing.

Jack O'Lanterns and The Tale Of Stingy Jack The jack-o‚Äô-lantern has a long history with Halloween, although these haunting visages haven‚Äôt always been carved out of pumpkins. Their origin comes from an Irish myth about Stingy Jack, who tricked the Devil for his own monetary gain. When Jack died, God didn‚Äôt allow him into heaven, and the Devil didn‚Äôt let him into hell, so Jack was sentenced to roam the earth for eternity. In Ireland, people started to carve demonic faces out of turnips to frighten away Jack‚Äôs wandering soul. When Irish immigrants moved to the U.S., they began carving jack-o‚Äô-lanterns from pumpkins, as these were native to the region. But how did jack-o‚Äô-lanterns become associated with Halloween? Halloween is based on the Celtic festival Samhain. It was believed that during Samhain the souls of those who had died traveled to the otherworld while other souls would return to visit the living. On Halloween night this ancient pagan tradition still continues on to this very day.

The phones of 50,000 individuals, including human rights activists and journalists, have been targeted by surveillance tools that were used by numerous governments. These tools can hack any iOS and Android phone, and there is no way to protect your device from it. It doesn't matter which apps you use, because the system is breached on a deeper level. According to the Snowden revelations from 2013, both Apple and Google are part of the global surveillance program that implies that these companies have to, among other things, implement backdoors into their mobile operating systems. These backdoors, usually disguised as security bugs, allow US agencies to access information on any smartphone in the world. The problem with such backdoors is that they are never exclusive to just one party. Anybody can exploit them. So if a US security agency can hack an iOS or Android phone, any other organization that uncovers the backdoors can do the same. Unsurprisingly, this is exactly what has been taking place: an Israeli company called NSO Group has been selling access to the spying tools that allowed third parties to hack tens of thousands of phones. Since at least 2018, I have been aware that one of my phone numbers was included in a list of potential targets of such surveillance tools (although a source from the NSO Group denies it). Personally, I wasn't worried: since 2011, when I was still living in Russia, I‚Äôve got used to assuming that all my phones were compromised. Anyone who gains access to my private data will be utterly disappointed ‚Äì they will have to go through thousands of concept designs for Telegram features and millions of messages related to our product development process. They won't find any important information there. However, these surveillance tools are also used against people far more prominent than me. For example, they were employed to spy on 14 heads of state. The existence of backdoors in crucial infrastructure and software creates a huge challenge for humanity. That's why I have been calling upon the governments of the world to start acting against the Apple-Google duopoly in the smartphone market and to force them to open their closed ecosystems and allow for more competition. So far, even though the current market monopolization increases costs and violates privacy and freedom of speech of billions, government officials have been very slow to act. I hope the news that they themselves have been targeted by these surveillance tools will prompt politicians to change their minds.
